<H5>  I. Main Points of the 1985 Telecommunications Reform </H5>
  A. Establishment of the Constitution Which Makes Entry 
into All Fields Possible 
  1. Introduction of the Principle of Competition to 
Carriers Which Establish Their Own Telecommunications Circuit 
Facilities (Classified as Type I carriers) 
  2. Liberalization of Circuit Usage (Classified as Type 
II carriers) 
  3. Deregulation of Terminal Equipment (Liberalization 
of telephone sets) 
  B. Improvement of Business Efficiency by the 
Privatization of NTT 
  1. Change of the Regulations on Tariffs (Decision of 
the Diet Approval by the Minister) 
  2. Abolition of Approval by the Minister for NTT's 
Budget 
  3. Elimination of the Regulation on NTT's Investment 
<H5>  II. The Situation after the Telecommunications Reform </H5>
  A. Market Entry 
  Japan has one of the most liberalized telecommunications 
markets in the world, comparable with that of the U.S.A. 



